spanGrp.span: A. and N. talk about the Goemai youth, education and farming.
For a continuation of this conversation see c00ANyouth2 to c00ANyouth4.
Okay, I want, the thing that I want, so that I talk a talk about, now, (these) kinds of our children who would go to a place that teaches learning (i.e., to schools).
To / hen zem / bi goezem noe / de hen k'wal k'wal k'a / nd'asoenoehoe / nye / jap men goet'ong men / mpe goeshe bi she.
When a person is able, uh, finds, uh, knowledge, (when) he would know the things, all the little things.
Gurum la b'oot / uh / kat / uh / bi man / ni t'ong man / bi / jap bi dip.
He would know how it goes with his market.
Ni t'ong man / boet'ong maan goe / loet'uk muk.
He would know how it goes with his field.
Ni t'ong man boemaan goe / zam muk.
He would know how it goes with his work that he would do.
Ni t'ong man boemaan goe / shit muk / goet'ong shin muk.
The person who refuses to do learning, (who) refuses to go to school, he wouldn't be able to know anything.
Gurum goepe / nyang goe shin bi she / nyang goe shin makaranta / ni t'ong b'oot goe man ndoe bi ba.
(He) wouldn't be able, uh, to--, count his money.
Boeb'oot / uh / de-goe n-- / kun sool muk ba.
(He) wouldn't be able to--, lie down (in writing) the little things to be able to write a letter (and) send (it) to his brother, or maybe--, to his mother's brother over there (in) a far away place.
Boeb'oot de-goe n-- / b'et / jap bi de-goe nb'oot de-goe nyil / longvilip poe / nyam nn muk ko-- / nk'en muk panang / pe goeseng ba.
Do you think that the thing is good?
Goe rang pe bi hok d'ong a?
How would (it) be (so that it) is good, hey?
T'ong shin a nd'ang d'ong ai?
Those school children--, uh, those, those who have learning.
Moejap makar-- / uh / moe / moegoe bi she.
You know, the earth nowadays, (in) the old times, when adult people--, uh, adult people (lit., people of black heads) moved (around) (i.e., were alive), they, uh, didn't learn anything.
Goe man / yil nd'asoenoe / a dok poeb'it / goepe / gurum k'-- / uh / gurum k'ek moetep leng / mep / uh / she ndoe bi ba.
They went out (in) their own ways (and) would sit.
Mep / p'at bi mep t'ong t'wot.
They counted their numbers with hands.
Mep wun bi wun mep / a ns'a.
And they, they, (do you) remember the thing (that) was a rope (that they) would tie?
Mep kuma mep k'oerek bi a k'yang t'ong d'yan yi?
I.e., they would tie knots in a rope (as a means of counting).
(They) would count the days of the month with it.
Money, when they found (it), they returned (and) sat here.
Sool / goepe mep la kat / mep buk doe t'wot.

Then when they took out the rope, so that they talk, they kept (it and) found, uh, the money gives, uh, little things that they found, behold, (here they) are, the things that they found, behold, (here they) are.
Sai mep la p'an a / t'yang hok / de mep k'wal yi / mep d'u kat / uh / sool poe / uh / jap bi goekat du na nd'e / bi goekat du na nd'e.
Okay, you see, this existing learning, this existing learning comes with very good things.
To / goe na karatu nd'ennoehoe / bi she nd'ennoehoe / doe goe bi goed'emen p'uur.
(It) comes with children to know everything.
Doe goe jap / de-goe man ko-mmoe.
Whatever child, this nowadays, (he) knows the things that he is inside.
Ko-la goenang nd'asoend'ennoehoe / man / bi goed'e muk nd'n.
The worries that everyone is inside (i.e., that everyone has), he knows the thing that he would do.
Weel goed'e ko-wuroe nd'n / ni man bi goet'ong shin muk.
Because of this, indeed, learning is very good.
Nyegoesek dai / bi she / d'ong p'uur.

Do you think that among the children, those who are going (for) learning now, (that among them there) are some (of) our children (and) they, sh--, get lost (i.e., stray from the right way) (and they) would hang around in the bush?
Goe rang pe / nd'n / jap moepe mep d'e t'ong men / bi she yi nd'asoenoe / d'emde jap men mep / sh-- / pap / t'ong leng nd'n s'et?
When (someone) goes out to go (for) learning, (he) returns (and) goes, so (he) should turn (and) arrive at a different place, so (he should) hang around, so (he) would turn.
D'a p'et de-goe maan bi she hok / ba maan goe yir yi ya ndoe pe goek'em / lang yi t'ong yir yi.
They do all the little things.
Mep / shin / gwen jap bi dip.
(This is) not really a good thing.
Because of this, the thing, the thing of earlier times, (it) again returns (and) comes back (and) arrives again on us.
Nyegoesek / bi / bi goedok poeb'it / ba ba wa wul zak-yit nk'a men.
Those, those children refuse now, uh, to go to the place of learning, everywhere.
Moe / moejap nyak d'em / uh / goe men / mpe bi she dip.
They, because they think that, that maybe even when they go (for) the learning, they would rise (and) not find any work here.
Mep / nyegoepe mep rang pe / de ko la du men bi she hok ma / t'ong yo du doe kat shit ba.
When you find, when you go to the school, to a good place, when you go and eat (i.e., succeed), you return home, you would return home to find work to do.
La goe kat / d'a goe maan mmakaranta hok / mpe goed'emen / d'a goe maan goe-goe s'oe / goe wa / t'ong goe wa de-goe kat shit goeshin.
If you refuse to, to do work, you would return (and) hang around, uh, you do the sort of thieving.
D'a goe nyang goe / goe shin shit / t'ong goe ba goe lang / uh / goe shin a nye mr hok.
Because your father would not find money to give you.
Nyepe nda goe boet'ong kat sool de-goe poe goe ba.
Your mother would not find money to give you.
Nn goe boet'ong kat sool de-goe poe goe ba.
The food that you would eat, you would (have to) search (it) by yourself, because you have already grown up.
S'oe goet'ong s'oe goe / t'ong goe tang toe goe k'a sak / nyepe goe f'yer d'emt'ei.
(Maybe) the people of (your) father who would return (and) go to--, so that (he) should put food (and) return home, he gives (the food to) you here, so that you eat (it and) return home.
Gwen nda goet'ong ba maan de-goe / de goe / loe s'oe yi / wa / ni doe poe goe de goe s'oe yi wa.
Because of this, I think like this, our children do a very bad thing now.
Nyegoesek / hen rang poenoe / jap men / shin bi goenyan nd'asoenoe p'uur.
The thing that we should do with them, uh, so that we pull their ears (i.e., rebuke or warn them).
Bi goepe t'ong moe shin ndoe mep toe / uh / de moe / del k'wam mep.
Okay, what/how would you think about (this), so how (would) we pull their ears?
To / bi goerang goe nd'ang k'a / de moe del k'wam mep a nd'ang?
You know, (for) one (thing), so that we talk (and) say, uh, this school where the children are stopping to go (to).
Goe man goeme / de moe k'wal moe yi / uh / makaranta nnoe goepe jap / d'e t'ong d'eet goe men yi.
The thing, we, those, (our) fathers and mothers, we make (it), uh, we came, (we) came with something that prevented them from learning.
Bi hok / men / moe moenda / ndoe moenn / moe sa / uh / moe doe / doe goe ndoe / bi goeden mep sek karatu.
You take the child, you are (there), uh, the kind of--, so that (he) should be going (for) learning.
Goe mang la / goe d'e / uh / nye / de goe d'e t'ong maan bi she yi.
You go out in the morning, you show him everything that (he) would do.
Goe p'et mb'itlung / goe nin ni goe ko-mmoe goepe t'ong shin.
You, uh, you have your load, you take (it and) return with it (and) give (it to) the child.
Goe / uh / goe goe le goe / goe mang goe ba nni goe poe la.
Money is at your place, you collect (it and) return with it (and) give (it to) the child.
Sool d'e pe goe / goe war goe ba nni goe poe la.
When (he) goes out (and) goes to sit over there, (when he) buys something to--, tobacco to smoke.
La p'et maan goe-goe t'ong panang / s'eet bi goen-- / toeb'a goens'wa.
(He) goes (and) comes out (and) hangs around in the bush smoking tobacco.
Maan p'et lang ns'et / t'ong s'wa toeb'a yi.
(He) returns (and) refuses here, uh, the learning, and (he) goes.
Ba doe nyang / uh / bi she hok goe maan.
This existing learning that he would refuse, he (would) put his mind to what?
Bi she goet'ong nyang muk nd'ennoe / ni b'et an muk a k'a mmoe?
Mr / mr / a ni toe kai.
He does not refuse, (it is) necessary.
This existing stealing, so (it is) a thing that (just) happens, or what? (I.e., what causes all this stealing?)
Mr nd'ennoehoe / a bi goedoe toe yi ko mmoe?
Okay, when the child takes to stealing, sit (him) down first, you should go with him, you yourself, however, (saying) that you (are) his father, you are not happy (with him).
To / la la mang a mr hok d'u ntyem muk / t'ong maan nni / goe goe k'a sak zak / goepe goe nda muk / t'yak goe pya ba.
The mother should not be happy.
(Tell him) if (he) exits (and) goes, just all the siblings would (be) at the thing of insulting (him).
La p'et maan / moejapnn kt dibit / goet'ong a mbi goenvang.
Because of this, (it is) how--, (it would be) good (if) we (would) rise (and) stand in order that we pull their ears.
Nyegoesek / a boe / d'ong moe yl moe d'yam / de-goe de moe del k'wam mep yi.
We should call them, the child, when you have a child who is there, everywhere, (you) would receive him, (you) return (and) sit (him) down here, (you) pull his ear, (you) speak thoroughly with him.
T'ong moe yong mep la / goepe goe goe la muk / goepe ni nd'e / ko-nnang / t'ong lap ni / ba doe d'u / del k'wam muk / kut kut ndoe ni nt'it.
This speech that you would speak, if (it) enters into his ears, (he) would tomorrow think (about it).
Kut goet'ong kut goe nnoe / la ru nk'wam muk / t'ong d'a rang nyerang.
Because of this, when people who know the things that he is doing.
Nyegoepe / la / gurum goepe ni / man / bi goepe ni d'e t'ong shin yi.
Your own (you say that), (he) would return (and he) would be a slave.
Mmak / t'ong ba t'ong d'e moekwaram.
He should roast chicken (and) give (them to) him.
Ni toe goe wus ke poe ni.
He should, uh, go (and) would buy water (and) return (and) give (it to) him here.
Ni toe goe / uh / maan t'ong s'eet haam ba doe poe ni.
A slave, they sit (= become) the same, or maybe, he was bigger than him in the past.
Kwaram / mep t'ong nkyat / ko kuma / ni dok f'yer ni.
Because of this, (this is) the thing that causes, (this is) the thing that comes.
A nyegoesek a bi goesa / a bi goedoe toe.
Uh, there are problems with (our) children.
We, the fathers, however, we should pull their ears thoroughly, (together) with the mothers.
Men / moenda zak / t'ong moe del k'wam mep nt'it / ndoe moenn.
Some children are there, they listen to the voice of their fathers.
D'emde jap d'e d'i / mep k'oeleng d'e moenda mep.
Other children are there, they don't listen to the voice of their fathers.
D'emde jap d'e d'i / mep k'oeleng d'e moenda mep ba.
Those existing ones who listen to the voice of their fathers, they go (for) this existing learning.
Moek'oeleng d'e moenda mep nd'ennoehoe / mep men / bi she nd'ennoehoe.
They just go, (they) would just go.
Mep men kt / t'ong men kt.

They, k--, (they) also pay attention, some (of) them perhaps, (if) maybe their father hasn't the money, or maybe nothing, he goes (in) his own way, when his father finds money, (he) would give (it to) him.
Mep / k-- / kula ma d'emde a mep o ko nda mep goe sool hok ko ndoe bi ba / ni maan bi muk / nda muk la kat sool t'ong poe ni.
And his father is a good person, when (he) finds (money), (he) gives (it to) him, his mother is a (good) person--, a good woman, when (she) finds (money), (she) gives (it to) him.
Nda muk kuma gurum goed'emen / la kat poe ni / nn muk gur-- / mat goed'emen / t'ong kat poe ni.
Behold, (here) he moves going, uh, the school is (there), when you return home this time, they say, he has come out a lawyer.
Ni nlang t'ong maan / uh / makaranta d'e / d'a goe wa d'em / mep yi / ni p'et lawyer.
When you return home this time, they say, he has done, uh, a doctor.
La goe wa d'em / mep yi ni shin / uh / doctor.
When you return home this time, they say, he has done, uh, a teacher.
La goe wa d'em / mep yi ni shin / uh / teacher.
Some people move on their own there turning to the side (i.e., getting side-tracked).
D'emde gurum leng mmep d'i / t'ong yir yi nt'oor.
They started this school together in the past.
Mep dok t'angoede makaranta nnoe kwa goeshak.
(Their) friend, he went, (their) friend, he tried hard and returned home, (he) would be a big person (now).
Mai ni maan / mai ni goe-goe ba wa / goe d'e goef'yer.

You, however, you, not yet, behold, (here) you move in the house, like this existing thing that you would have said, you have maybe turned into someone who roasts meat, you have maybe turned into someone who goes (to deliver) messages, you have maybe turned into someone who fetches water, you have maybe turned into someone who--, splits wood--, splits wood (i.e., makes firewood).

Goe zak / goe toe / t'ekgoed'i / goe nlang / nlu / goebi goet'ong k'wal goe nd'ennoehoe / goe p'iring ma goewus lwa / goe p'iring ma / goemaan paar / goe p'iring ma goerap hangoed'e / goe p'iring ma goe-- / kyak / sh'-- / kyak sh'ep.
Okay, where is its goodness in this existing thing?
To / goed'ong muk d'e nnang nd'n bi nd'ennoehoe?
You see, the thing that causes (it), I am just, my heart is getting sad with our children who, because of the thing that they are doing now.
Goe na / bi goesa toe / hen d'e kt / k'yak noe d'e t'ong dam yi ndoe jap men goepe / k'a bi goepe mep d'e nshin yi nd'asoenoe.
A person who knows the reason, then, some person when (he) sits, so that (he) should talk with you, he doesn't go to do this existing thing.
Gurum goeman yit nye / sai / ndoe gurum la t'ong toe / de goe k'wal ndoe goe yi maan goe shin bi nd'ennoe ba.
So you would talk yourself, right, you see maybe, behold, the thing is right in front of me.
T'ong goe k'wal toe goe k'a sak yi / kai / goe na ko / bi na nd'e bantyem noe.
If I refuse to find knowledge, I will not find food that I would eat.
Hen la nyang goe kat bi man / hen t'ong kat s'oe goet'ong s'oe noe ba.
I would turn into a message boy.
The children of the neighbours who are the same age, another one (would say that) I am bigger than them, (but) my trousers are torn, my knees hang outside.
Jap moenye goepe / yi men nkyat / nde ma hen f'yer mep toe / wando noe ter / foerem noe / leng goesampe.
You would not be able (to be) on the field to go (there).
Boegoe b'oot a nzam goemaan ba.
You would not be able (with) anything to do (it).
Boegoe b'oot a ndoe bi de-goe nshin ba.
You should not go to your school.
Because of this, we (should) restore some intelligence.
Here first, this time--, you know (that) the Goemai, they were the first in the past, everyone, of his (= the Goemai) fathers, (they were the first) with learning, really.
B'ak ntyem / d'em-- / goe man Goemai / mep dok d'e ntyem dip / moenda muk / goe bi she dai.
The Goemai were the first in the past.
Everything, in the past, they, uh, uh, return to do whatever thing, our heads, uh, our mouths (were) one.
Ko-bi mmoe / mep dok / uh / uh / buk de-goe shin bi mmoe / k'ek men / uh / pe men goeme.
Uh, we put our heads together.
Uh / moe maam k'ek men goeshak.
We, they feared all of us.
But nowadays, we have turned again into a laughing matter.
Amma nd'asoenoe d'em / b'ep moe p'iring bi swar toe.
This one takes his neighbour (and) goes to insult (him) there.
Goennoe / mang goenye maan goe vang panang.
This one takes his neighbour (and) goes to insult (him) there, (it is) because of what?
Goennoe mang goenye / maan goe vang panang / a nye bi mmoe?
The thing that you would do doesn't exist.
Bi goepe t'ong goe shin wan.
(You have nothing to do,) only the thing, uh, bad things just sit this time, so (they) just sit with it.
Sai / bi / uh / nye goenyan d'em t'ong kt / kt t'ong yi nni.
You would talk a talk (and) say, some people, some people, when they go and do good things, (they) return again with them, the speech despises them (i.e., those that do good things).
T'ong goe k'wal k'wal yin / ndoe mutane / ndoe gurum la maan goe shin bi goed'emen / ba ba nni / kut kyeni ni.
When they go and do good things, (they) return again with them, the speech despises them.
D'a maan goe shin / bi goed'emen ba nni / kut kyeni ni.
Okay, (he) would tomorrow, (at) your settlement when (...).
To / t'ong d'a / ndoe lu gwen t'atnang (...)
